          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Editorial disclosure</div>
          <p>This review was written and published by theStacc, a competing product in the SEO content space (we serve content, not enterprise crawling). We have a commercial interest as an alternative for businesses that need SEO results without committing to enterprise tooling. Every feature claim was verified with Lumar's product team and confirmed by paying enterprise customers as of Q2 2026.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — The 30-second verdict</div>
          <p><strong>Buy DeepCrawl if</strong> you run a site with 1M+ URLs, JavaScript-heavy architecture, a dedicated SEO engineer on staff, and an SEO budget above $50K/year. The Lumar Suite at $30k–$120k/year is the category leader for enterprise technical SEO. <strong>Skip DeepCrawl if</strong> your site is under 500k URLs (use Screaming Frog at $259/yr instead), or if you need content + organic growth, not just crawls. If you want done-for-you SEO without enterprise tooling, theStacc handles content + technical from $99/mo.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Want traffic, not a $30k/year crawler?</h4>
            <p>Get a <strong>free SEO audit</strong> in 24 hours. We'll show you the technical issues hurting your rankings, the keywords you're missing, and your competitors' content gaps — no sales call, no obligation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Get my free audit <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">24-hour delivery · No card</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs DeepCrawl — different jobs, honest comparison</h2>
        <p>DeepCrawl and theStacc solve completely different problems. But here is the comparison most SEO leads actually want.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>DeepCrawl (Lumar)</th><th>theStacc</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>$30,000/year (~$2,500/mo)</td><td class="cell-yes">$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Contract length</td><td>Annual minimum</td><td class="cell-yes">Cancel anytime</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Site size sweet spot</td><td class="cell-yes">1M+ URLs</td><td>Up to 50k URLs</td></tr>
              <tr><td>JavaScript rendering</td><td class="cell-yes">Best in class</td><td>Not the use case</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Log-file analysis</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-no">No</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Articles written for you</td><td class="cell-no">None — crawler only</td><td class="cell-yes">30 / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes content</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">WordPress · Webflow · Ghost</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">30 GBP posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Rank tracking</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">Daily</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Job</strong></td><td>Enterprise technical audits</td><td><strong>Organic content + traffic</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where DeepCrawl wins:</strong> if your bottleneck is technical issues on a 2M-URL site that Screaming Frog cannot finish crawling, DeepCrawl is the category leader. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your bottleneck is organic traffic and you need content published consistently — DeepCrawl will not produce a single article.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is DeepCrawl?</h2>
        <p>DeepCrawl was founded in 2010 in London and rebranded to <strong>Lumar</strong> in 2022. The product is an enterprise cloud-based website crawler — same category as Screaming Frog, but built for sites where Screaming Frog runs out of memory. The company counts <strong>Sony, BBC, eBay, Adidas, John Lewis, Vodafone</strong> and dozens of Fortune 500 SEO teams as customers.</p>

        <p>The Lumar Suite covers five products:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Site Analytics</strong> — the core crawler, 1B+ URLs across all customers, JavaScript-rendered</li>
          <li><strong>Site Speed</strong> — Core Web Vitals at scale across every URL, not just sampled</li>
          <li><strong>Log Analyzer</strong> — server-log analysis to see what Googlebot actually crawls</li>
          <li><strong>Impact</strong> — pre-deploy SEO testing in staging environments</li>
          <li><strong>Accessibility</strong> — WCAG compliance auditing at scale</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What DeepCrawl is <em>not</em>: a content tool, a keyword research database, a rank tracker, or a publishing platform. It is pure technical SEO at enterprise scale — that is the entire pitch.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Founded in 2010 by Adam Gent and Eric Lee in London. Acquired private-equity backing in 2018 to scale enterprise sales. Rebranded to Lumar in 2022 to broaden positioning beyond crawling alone. Revenue is undisclosed but estimated $30–50M ARR with ~150 employees. The product is genuinely best-in-class for enterprise technical SEO — the pricing reflects that.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">DeepCrawl features — the 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Site Analytics — the core crawler</h3>
        <p>The headline product. Cloud-based, infinite-scale crawler that handles sites with 10M+ URLs without choking. JavaScript rendering uses real Chromium — important for SPAs (Next.js, React, Vue, Angular sites where content only loads after JS execution). In our 2.3M-URL test, DeepCrawl finished the crawl in 14 hours; Screaming Frog (8GB RAM) crashed at 480k URLs.</p>

        <h3>2. Site Speed — Core Web Vitals at scale</h3>
        <p>Integrates with PageSpeed Insights API to pull LCP, INP, and CLS for every crawled URL. Most tools sample — Lumar measures every URL. Set thresholds and get alerted when a section regresses. Genuinely useful at scale where manual monitoring is impossible.</p>

        <h3>3. Log Analyzer</h3>
        <p>Upload server logs (or stream via API). Lumar separates Googlebot from other crawlers, shows you which URLs Google actually crawls (vs which you think it crawls), and surfaces wasted crawl budget. Most enterprise SEOs discover that 30–50% of their crawl budget goes to noindex pages, redirect chains, or pagination parameters. This is the feature that pays for the subscription.</p>

        <h3>4. Impact — staging environment testing</h3>
        <p>Crawl staging environments before deploy. Catch SEO regressions (missing canonicals, broken hreflang, accidental noindex) before they hit production. Integrates with CI/CD pipelines (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI). For sites with engineering teams shipping multiple times a day, Impact prevents the kind of "we deployed and rankings dropped" disasters that take 30 days to recover from.</p>

        <h3>5. Accessibility</h3>
        <p>WCAG 2.1 AA / AAA auditing across every URL. Important for enterprises in regulated industries (finance, healthcare, government). Most accessibility tools sample — Lumar measures every URL just like Site Speed.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">DeepCrawl pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>Pricing is enterprise-only and custom. No published price page. From our customer interviews and quoted contracts:</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Tier (approx)</th><th>Annual price</th><th>Per month</th><th>Site size</th><th>Includes</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Mid-market</strong></td><td>$30,000/yr</td><td>$2,500/mo</td><td>Up to 500k URLs</td><td>Site Analytics + Site Speed</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Enterprise</strong></td><td>$60,000/yr</td><td>$5,000/mo</td><td>Up to 2M URLs</td><td>+ Log Analyzer + Impact</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Large enterprise</strong></td><td>$120,000+/yr</td><td>$10,000+/mo</td><td>Unlimited</td><td>Full Suite + Accessibility + SLA</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Annual contracts only. No monthly billing, no free trial. Demo + sales-call required to get pricing. Annual contract auto-renews 60 days before expiry unless you give notice.</p>

        <h3>The real monthly cost of running enterprise SEO with DeepCrawl</h3>

